            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Todd Erickson\u2019s story is etched in the silicon of a bygone era. Raised in Sacramento by a mechanic father and a bookkeeper mother, Todd was instilled with a practical, roll-up-your-sleeves work ethic. He was the kid who took apart the family VCR just to see how it worked. In the early 1990s, he enrolled in a Computer Information Systems program at a state college, but found the curriculum lagged far behind the real-world explosion happening just a few hours west.\n\nImpulsive and hungry for action, Todd dropped out after three semesters for an entry-level IT support gig in the Bay Area during the first dot-com boom. It was a pivotal choice. While others chased venture capital, Todd learned the unglamorous, essential work of keeping networks running. He survived the bust because his skills were foundational, not speculative. Over two decades, he methodically climbed the ladder from systems administrator to engineer, and finally, to Principal Solutions Architect. He is the veteran who understands how legacy systems connect to the cloud because he physically built them.\n\nHis career ascent, however, shadowed his personal life. A long marriage, which produced a now-adult daughter living in Portland, ended amicably in his late forties. The divorce prompted him to move from the suburbs into San Francisco proper, settling into a comfortable apartment in Noe Valley. He appreciates the neighborhood's quiet, village-like feel, a stark contrast to the sterile tech campus where he spends his days.\n\nTodd\u2019s routine is structured: a morning walk for coffee, the corporate shuttle to his SoMa office, and evenings often spent decompressing with a craft beer and a home-cooked meal. He maintains a small circle of old friends, mostly peers who also remember a pre-Google San Francisco. He feels a disconnect from the younger tech workforce\u2014their ambition is familiar, but their world is not his.\n\nFinancially secure, Todd\u2019s aspirations have shifted from professional to personal. He dreams of scaling back, perhaps taking on a mentorship role or starting a small consultancy that allows him to travel. He wants to visit the national parks he\u2019s only seen on screen savers and finally architect a life beyond the system diagrams that have defined him for thirty years."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the fluorescent hum in that state college classroom, the professor droning on about legacy code he already felt was obsolete. Outside, the world was crackling with the energy of the early web. He closed his textbook mid-lecture with a profound clarity. The real work wasn't in this stuffy room; it was in the server closets of the Bay Area. He walked out and never went back, a decision that cemented his lifelong trust in practical application over prescribed theory. This occurred in the mid-1990s.\n\n2.\nThe air in SoMa was silent in 2002. He\u2019d walk past glass lobbies filled with stacked Aeron chairs, monuments to failed IPOs. While others panicked, Todd felt a quiet hum of purpose. He was still needed. His job wasn't about a stock price, but about the physical racks and blinking lights\u2014the unglamorous bones of the internet. That survival wasn't luck; it was proof that building something real would always outlast the hype. It gave him a deep, foundational confidence.\n\n3.\nHis daughter, then about seven, was sobbing over her favorite cassette tape, its brown ribbon mangled by the boombox. Instead of tossing it, Todd sat at the kitchen table with tweezers and Scotch tape, patiently untangling and splicing the delicate film for an hour. The smile she gave him when it played again felt more significant than any system he\u2019d ever brought online. It was a tangible reminder that his skills could be used for care, not just for code. This happened in the late 1990s.\n\n4.\nAfter the movers left his new Noe Valley apartment post-divorce, Todd sat on the floor with a beer, watching the fog roll in. The suburban house had been full of shared history, but this space was an empty diagram waiting for him to draw the plans. It wasn't sadness he felt, but a quiet, unnerving freedom. For the first time in twenty years, he was the sole architect of his own evening, and his own life. This took place in his late forties.\n\n5.\nOn the corporate shuttle, he overheard two engineers earnestly debating the merits of a new Javascript framework as if it were a moral imperative. Todd didn't feel cynical, just\u2026 distant. He remembered the visceral thrill of simply getting a network to talk to another across a building. Their ambition was familiar, but their world felt abstract, a software layer built upon the concrete foundation he\u2019d laid. It was the moment he knew he was ready to build something just for himself again. This happened just last year."
